dwm - dynamic window manager
============================
dwm is an extremely fast, small, and dynamic window manager for X.


Requirements
------------
In order to build dwm you need the Xlib header files.


Installation
------------
Edit config.mk to match your local setup (dwm is installed into
the /usr/local namespace by default).

Afterwards enter the following command to build and install dwm (if
necessary as root):

    make clean install


Running dwm
-----------
Add the following line to your .xinitrc to start dwm using startx:

    exec dwm

In order to connect dwm to a specific display, make sure that
the DISPLAY environment variable is set correctly, e.g.:

    DISPLAY=foo.bar:1 exec dwm

(This will start dwm on display :1 of the host foo.bar.)

In order to display status info in the bar, you can do something
like this in your .xinitrc:

    while xsetroot -name "`date` `uptime | sed 's/.*,//'`"
    do
    	sleep 1
    done &
    exec dwm


Configuration
-------------
The configuration of dwm is done by creating a custom config.h
and (re)compiling the source code.


noirLang session
----------------
This tree includes a complete noirLang dwm session.  LightDM starts it
through `/usr/local/bin/noir-session`, which applies display settings,
starts the autostart helpers, and then execs `/usr/local/bin/dwm`.


Display layout
--------------
`scripts/noir-displays` configures the current laptop setup with the
internal panel on `DP-2` at 1920x1080 144 Hz and the HDMI monitor on
`HDMI-0` at 1920x1080 60 Hz.  Override the output names or refresh rates
with `NOIR_LAPTOP_OUTPUT`, `NOIR_EXTERNAL_OUTPUT`, `NOIR_LAPTOP_RATE`,
and `NOIR_EXTERNAL_RATE`.


Application launcher
--------------------
`Super+Space` and the `noirLang` bar label open `scripts/noir-launcher`.
It builds a filtered list from visible `.desktop` applications, keeps app
icons through Rofi dmenu metadata, and launches the selected entry with
`gio launch`.


Network and Bluetooth
---------------------
The network status segment opens Gazelle, a NetworkManager TUI, when
`gazelle` is installed.  The Bluetooth segment opens `bluetuith`, with
`bluetui` and Blueman kept only as fallbacks.  Status text is generated
by `scripts/noir-network` and `scripts/noir-bluetooth`.


Audio and screenshots
---------------------
`scripts/noir-volume` handles the bar volume text, scroll actions, and
small YAD volume/output controls.  `scripts/noir-screenshot` uses
Flameshot with X11 legacy capture enabled and sends interactive captures
to the clipboard while also using the configured screenshots directory.
